index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Judge Allows Former 'Apprentice' Contestant to Press Defamation Lawsuit Against Trump; Lawyers for the president also had sought postponing the case until after his term</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A New York judge on Tuesday ruled that President Donald Trump must face a defamation suit brought by a former contestant on "The Apprentice" who accused him in 2016 of making unwanted sexual advances.</Para><Para>The <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018-03-20Zervos-Trump.pdf">ruling</ELink> came in <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-apprentice-contestant-sues-trump-for-defamation-1484685667">a lawsuit brought by Summer Zervos</ELink> in state court in Manhattan in January 2017. Weeks before the election, Ms. Zervos accused Mr. Trump of kissing and groping her without her permission about a decade earlier. After Mr. Trump suggested on Twitter, at campaign rallies and during presidential debates that her story was a "hoax" and "phony," and made up to get attention, Ms. Zervos sued, claiming he had "debased and denigrated" her "with false statements."</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Mr. Trump has said the lawsuit has no merit and has vehemently denied the sexual-misconduct accusations, which Ms. Zervos made during a news conference in the wake of the release of a 2005 "Access Hollywood" tape of Mr. Trump talking lewdly about women.</Para><Para>His lawyers also argued that the litigation should at least be postponed until the end of his presidency, saying "the United States Constitutionâ€¦immunizes the President from being sued in state court while in office" and that defending himself in the proceeding would "interfere with his ability to perform his duties."</Para><Para>In an 18-page ruling, Justice Jennifer Schecter rejected the president's argument for delay, concluding the former "Apprentice" contestant could have her day in court.</Para><Para>"No one is above the law," wrote Judge Schecter. "Nothing in the Supremacy Clause of the United States Constitution even suggests that the President cannot be called to account before a state court for wrongful conduct that bears no relationship to any federal executive responsibility."</Para><Para>She continued: "In the end, there is absolutely no authority for dismissing or staying a civil action related purely to unofficial conduct because defendant is the President of the United States."</Para><Para>In a statement Tuesday, Mr. Trump's lawyer, Marc Kasowitz, said the president would appeal the decision and seek to halt the case while higher courts review Judge Schecter's opinion.</Para><Para>"We disagree with this decision, which is wrong as a matter of Constitutional law," Mr. Kasowitz stated.</Para><Para>Attorney Gloria Allred, who represents Ms. Zervos, couldn't immediately be reached for comment.</Para><Para>Tuesday's ruling relied partly on the U.S. Supreme Court's 1997 ruling that Paula Jones could sue then-President Bill Clinton in federal court over conduct that predated his administration.</Para><Para>The Supreme Court has said that presidents are "absolutely immune from civil damage lawsuits" for conduct within the "outer perimeter" of their official responsibilities but could be forced to answer to complaints over purely private acts.</Para><Para>The high court held that Ms. Jones's sexual-harassment complaint could proceed against Mr. Clinton because those allegations concerned personal, private conduct.</Para><Para>The Supreme Court has never made clear whether the immunity shield applies to a president's conduct during a campaign before taking office.</Para><Para>Lawyers for Mr. Trump had argued that a stay in the case was "warranted given the significant risk that this action will interfere with the President's executive responsibilities to the detriment of the public" and that allowing a state court to hear the case makes the proceeding more constitutionally problematic.</Para><Para>They also argued that comments alleged to be defamatory didn't identify Ms. Zervos but were more general references to stories about sexual-misconduct allegations against him.</Para><Para>Write to Jacob Gershman at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:jacob.gershman@wsj.com">jacob.gershman@wsj.com</ELink> and Joe Palazzolo at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:joe.palazzolo@wsj.com">joe.palazzolo@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-stormy-history-the-seven-year-battle-between-the-president-and-the-porn-star-1521561532">The Seven-Year Battle Between the President and the Porn Star</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stormy-danielss-lawyer-buys-lie-detector-video-1521575056">Stormy Daniels's Lawyer Buys Lie-Detector Video</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/2018-03-20Zervos-Trump.pdf">Judge Schecter's Ruling in Zervos v. Trump Suit</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Jacob Gershman and Joe Palazzolo </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-allows-former-apprentice-contestant-to-press-defamation-lawsuit-against-trump-1521578734" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

